<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-952-134  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 952 134.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Modern Office Technology  Jan 1989 v34 n1 p97(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Will the early birds get the WORMs? (records management) (1989Buyers Reference Issue) (buyers guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brindza, Stephen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A good records management plan includes a regulated form ofaccess, a way to refile and a way to enter new records.andP;  The mostexciting prospects for 1989 are optical disk medium andintegrating laser disks into present systems.andP;  Office staff havebeen slow to accept Write Once-Read Many (WORM) systems, but thissituation is expected to change by 1992.andP;  Some businesses storetheir data on CD-ROM disks.andP;  They send the data to a CDmanufacturer on a floppy disk or tape and the CD manufacturerpresses the information onto a CD-ROM disk.andP;  One 5.25-inch CDholds 1,500 floppy disks.andP;  Another development iscomputer-assisted retrieval (CAR) systems.andP;  CAR systems permitusers to access any type of storage media and display theinformation on a workstation screen without knowing where the datais stored.andP;  A list of suppliers of document storage retrieval andmicrographics equipment is included.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PurchasesOffice AutomationRecords ManagementInformation Storage and RetrievalMicrographicsWORMCD-ROM.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Records management reference chart. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>